<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0079</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 5.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="540" height="74" alt="" style="float:left; margin:0pt 9pt" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0079</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> the Association of Teachers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">About ATL</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL, the education union, is an independent, registered trade union and professional association, representing approximately 160,000 teachers, head teachers, lecturers and support staff in maintained and independent nurseries, schools, sixth form, tertiary and further education colleges in the United Kingdom. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">AMiE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is the trade union and professional association for leaders and managers in colleges and schools, and is a distinct section of ATL. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL is concerned that the current Government’s policy is that no new school can open unless it is an academy or a free school. We would like to see a more transparent process for determining which academies go ahead, with full disclosure of all academy proposals and oversight of public expenditure, including details of public money spent in establishing academies. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The number of academies and free schools has made the role of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in overseeing them impossible. Overall ATL believes that the presumption that intervention and support comes from the centre, or regionally, is flawed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Local authorities are responsible for all children and young people in their area, whatever provision they need. Collaboration between schools is a vital element of improvement and local authorities still have the status and will to encourage and lead it</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Academy chains lack legitimate authority, primarily because they are properly accountable to no-one and communities have no democratic levers to influence their behaviour and priorities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL’s concerns over academy status for primary schools is that this is ideologically driven rather than starting from the position of what might work best in terms of improving children’s education.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We oppose forced conversions and are concerned about the growing number of reports of heavy handed and undemocratic approaches to primary schools. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL is not convinced the Government will take alternatives to sponsored academy status seriously. We firmly believe that converting to an academy is not the only, or even the best way to improve outcomes at a school.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We welcome the Select Committee’s inquiry into the establishment, operation and future direction of the academies and free schools programme. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">AiME</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> represent teachers, leaders and support staff who work in academies and free schools, and our response to the Select Committee draws upon their experiences.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We have serious concerns about the intention from the Coalition Government that all schools should become academies. We have long opposed the academy programme as we believe it fragments provision, reduces </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">accountability and has proved costly, taking money away from maintained schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Many of the freedoms granted to academies and free schools do not have the education of children and young people at the centre. Autonomy for headteachers is spurious as academy status can be imposed by the Secretary of State, and power is handed to academy sponsors rather than school leadership.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL is concerned by evidence from recent research that suggests </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is having a limited impact on narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children. A study led by Professor Stephen </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Gorard</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> from the University of Durham, looked at the links between segregation and type of school. The analysis of 36 local authority areas revealed that converter academies have higher levels of segregation as they have much lower rates of children eligible for free school meals than the national average.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The attainment of disadvantaged pupils in academies has also been called into question. Research from the Centre for Economic Performance found little evidence that academies helped those in the bottom 10% and 20% of achievement distribution. The conclusion was that academies only had small beneficial effects on overall pupil performance and there was an absence of consistent evidence of improvements for ‘tail students’.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Similarly, Professor Terry Wrigley disputes the claims that academy status in itself will benefit disadvantaged young people as his analysis found that only in the longest established academies were disadvantaged young people slightly more likely to achieve 5 A*-C GCSEs or equivalent – with a marginal difference of one or two pupils out of every hundred.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Committee will be familiar with the RSA Academies Commission report which found that despite impressive steps in some cases to address social inclusion, this was not consistent across all academies.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> The Commission commented that some academies would rather manipulate admissions than exercise strong leadership when undertaking school improvement, and has called for an end to such practices.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL supports the Commission’s conclusion that academies and maintained schools should be placed on a common footing regarding admissions and should operate within a framework of open and fair compliance.  Proposals included identifying an independent appeals service for disputes over individual cases relating to admissions, and requiring each academy to publish socio-economic data, about who applies to it and who is admitted. These ideas need revisiting to ensure that there is a more level playing field in the future.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL disagrees with the current Government’s policy that no new school can open unless it is an academy or a free school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Despite assurances from the Secretary of State, the process for establishing new academies and free schools has suffered from a lack of rigour and transparency. Recent high profile cases illustrate this including Al-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Madinah</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> school which was approved without being in a fit condition to open and teach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL calls for a more transparent process for determining which academies and free schools go ahead, with full disclosure of all proposals and oversight of public expenditure, including details of public money spent in establishing academies and free schools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We also support a ‘fit and proper person’ test for sponsors and the establishment of a body responsible for financial oversight. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The rush to open academies and free schools has resulted in schools opening in areas where there is no need for extra school places</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">at the cost of £241m to the taxpayer.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Allowing ad hoc openings has meant that there are no new schools planned for more than half the areas where there are severe shortages of places. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL endorses the calls from the Public Accounts Committee that the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> urgently needs to be more rigorous about how applications for new schools are assessed, with needs and value for money given far greater priority – at the moment, the approach is contributing to the growing crisis of school places. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Given the rapid expansion in the number of academies and free schools the role of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and Secretary of State in overseeing them has become impossible – it is not feasible to manage these schools from the centre and identify and intervene in schools where there are issues, in a timely manner. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Support needs to be in place before an academy is failing, or the Secretary of State is ultimately letting down children and young people. It often appears to be the case that schools in difficulties have been identified through whistleblowers, which clearly highlights the issue with central control. Problems are not being spotted early enough. For example, the recent case of Kings Science Academy showed that there was a long delay between problems first being reported and action being taken.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">When interventions and support from the Secretary of State in failing academies do take place, these appear to be lacking in any consistency or quality controls.  Whilst the government claims that many academies respond well to the issues that are picked up in pre-warning letters, it is not clear who monitors the processes and support put in place. The closure of the Discovery Free School in December 2013 highlighted that there had been little or no improvement in teaching and learning since the school had been put in special measures in May 2013.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> This again suggests that the intervention process is currently inadequate. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL members who had experienced interventions from the Secretary of State in their schools said that teachers often lacked information about what was happening. They commented that support was often available at the beginning and end of the period of required improvement rather than throughout when it was perhaps most needed.  The responses in our survey indicate there is an absence of clear evidence of what works in terms of the Secretary of State’s interventions. If these examples exist, they should be disseminated more widely in the sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Our members felt that the central approach to intervention and support could leave teachers feeling undermined and under intense pressure from workloads and monitoring. To improve this situation, they stressed the importance of involving staff in the process, identifying together what was needed to improve the school, and setting out a clear timescale with all staff.  They felt that changes were often made in a rush in response to the intervention, which had to be unpicked at a later stage, and that a more considered approach with support from another nearby school with relevant experience and knowledge could be more productive for all involved. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL believes that local expertise can play a valuable role in ensuring successful interventions in schools. The presumption that intervention and support comes from the centre, or regionally, is flawed. The number and geography of England’s schools precludes central oversight and local authorities are best placed for this role - with their knowledge of their local area, they are in a stronger position to intervene at an early stage where a school is failing, compared to remote academy chains or the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL’s position is that collaboration between schools is a vital element of improvement and many local authorities still have the status and will to encourage and lead it. Funding and powers to intervene are required so councils can fulfil their role in driving and supporting school improvement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">With the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> plans to establish a new body (Headteacher boards) to oversee the non-maintained sector, it is essential that this body is representative, including unions, local authorities, academy chains and education experts, rather than solely relying on direct appointees by the Secretary of State. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individuals schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The middle tier: a view from the profession</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, ATL’s short paper, argues that local authorities – and not new or other existing organisations – should be the ‘middle tier’ body to support and challenge schools</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> with democratic accountability</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Local authorities are responsible for all children and young people in their area, whatever provision they need. Local authorities’ oversight should include: planning for an appropriate supply of school places; admissions, exclusions, and transportation as part of a system of fair access to schools; school improvement; accountability of schools to parents and the community; SEN provision and providing or brokering services for schools.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Academisation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, particularly at a time of reduced budgets, has led to some duplication and some local authority functions of the recent past being unsustainable. At the same time, it is debatable as to whether all academies can fulfil these roles adequately. ATL members have reported mixed experiences about buying in services, with some continuing to buy from the local authority, and others sourcing cheaper options. This inevitably leads to an unequal situation, and the Committee should consider how this might be addressed.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In addition, the recent PAC report found that roles and responsibilities between different organisations have not been clarified, resulting in inconsistencies in accountability, performance monitoring and intervention (previously carried out by local authorities) across different localities and academy structures.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL believes that to address these issues with different experiences in different areas, local authorities should be re-empowered by government in relation to all schools in their area. The middle tier must develop and promulgate a vision of a shared purpose for schools, one which can bind and inspire schools and their communities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">It is necessary not just to hold schools to account but to ensure there is accountability to local communities in any area, with a responsibility to every child. It is difficult to think of an effective mechanism for this accountability which does not have a democratic basis. The latest plans from the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> on regional chancellors does not provide this.  Without local and democratic oversight, individuals and whole cohorts risk slipping through the net. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Local Authorities also play a vital role in ensuring that academies can carry out their legally binding obligations on Union facility time, as laid out in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Sections 168 and 178 of the Trade Union and Labour Relations (Consolidation) Act 1992. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Academies and free schools have been receptive to the idea of facilities “pots”, and have signed up to the TUC Model Agreement on Union Recognition. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There are a number of advantages of such arrangements for academies and free schools, including maintaining a working relationship with all schools in the area; ensuring there </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is no confusion or dispute when LA-employed staff visit an academy or free school, or vice versa; safeguarding the legal right of staff to be represented at work by a recognised union; and providing a mechanism for academies and free schools to meet their legal obligations which is cost-effective and also minimises the disruption to pupils in the classroom. Local authorities should be encouraged to maintain such arrangements whereby academies can contribute to shared union facilities arrangements and benefit from consistent and timely trade union representation for their staff.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Academy chains lack legitimate authority, primarily because they are properly accountable to no-one and communities have no democratic levers to influence their behaviour and priorities. This is a fundamental weakness of the schools landscape as the number of academies and free schools has increased. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Their lack of local responsibility and relation to local areas are primary reasons why academy chains are unsuitable to take on many of the responsibilities we believe local authorities can and should. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Given the current policy context, the chains can and should do more, but crucially should be held accountable for all they do in education. We believe the chains should, like local authorities, face inspection for their role in driving school improvement. It is clear from the chief inspector that Ofsted takes the same view.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, it would be misplaced for the committee to assume that Ofsted is necessarily capable given the problem it has with the quality and consistency of inspections and it would be wrong-headed to make chains more powerful. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL members who work in academy chains, felt that there was a need for good practice in academy chains to be disseminated more effectively, and that it was important to bear in mind that there is no one size fits all business model for chains. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Another issue that ATL members highlighted in their responses was around the need to rigorously monitor how money provided for SEN is being used by chains, and whether those running special schools that become academies have the relevant experience. The need for transparency was a common thread in many of the comments from our members.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The number of primary schools converting to academy status remains comparatively low – 9% of all primary schools in England - despite the policy drive from central Government. ATL’s concerns over academy status for primary schools is that this is ideologically driven rather than starting from the </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">position of what might work best in terms of improving children’s education.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We oppose forced conversions and are concerned about the growing number of reports of heavy handed and undemocratic approaches to primary schools. Schools should be able to choose whether or not they want to become academies, with parents, governors, pupils and the local community able to have their say.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL would not want to see a situation where there is a rapid expansion of primary academies which are not part of their local community of schools. This risks further fragmentation and weakened accountability at a local level in the school system. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Our survey of ATL and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">AiME</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> members teaching in primary schools that have converted to academy status indicated that there are positive experiences around curriculum freedom, flexibility to target resources, and collaboration with other schools in Multi Academy Trusts. However, we know that confident schools of all kinds feel they have the freedom to innovate and ATL believes that this should apply to all schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The main issues that our members encountered were around increased administration loads, challenges in finding reputable support services, and having to learn business skills very rapidly.  A survey by the IAA supports these experiences and pointed to the need for more financial management support, and more time during the conversion process to support governors and SLT on academy finances.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> There is very little expertise in commercial accounting in the sector, and there is a risk of even more wasteful expenditure if this is not addressed which could end up being far in excess of any other efficiency gains. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Overall, the costs for primary schools can be disproportionate to the benefits – particularly around the capacity of small schools to provide the administration and back up that was previously the role of the local authority.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL also believes that lessons should be learnt from the rapid expansion of secondary school academies and free schools – in particular, having robust processes in place to assess the suitability of sponsors, providing support for schools taking on new financial responsibilities and monitoring performance.  These issues have been highlighted yet again in the recent NAO report and it is not acceptable for the programme to continue without proper accountability for how public money is being spent.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Information about the costs of conversion should also be transparent, or it will be hard to assess whether this represents value for money.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL is not convinced the Government will take alternatives to sponsored academy status seriously. We firmly believe that converting to an academy is not the only, or even the best way to improve outcomes at a school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ATL and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">AiME</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> members feel that the judgement of ‘failing’ is not a robust measure, based on snapshot data at a particular time. It is worth bearing in mind that some primary schools may be struggling due to the decreasing support from local authorities in the changing education landscape.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The RSA Academies Commission argued persuasively that the federation of primary schools should be encouraged without an immediate emphasis on academy status. The report also emphasised that many primary schools have strong relationships with their local authority and value collaboration with other schools in the area. Our members also highlighted that in their experiences, support from the local authority in terms of action plans, improvement partners and links with other schools can be effective. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> should learn from the recent case of Snaresbrook Primary where the local authority replaced the Headteacher, chair of governors, brokered partnership with a nearby school, provided specialist consultants, and avoided the need for a conversion to an academy which was opposed by parents and the community.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In summary, a number of alternatives to academy status are already available and the evidence of what works from these experiences should be taken into account:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Strong local authorities intervening quickly in cases where schools are performing poorly and providing dedicated support to improve</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Federations of primary schools – with a 2011 Ofsted’s report outlining the effective leadership that comes from this approach</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Local partnerships with other successful schools in the area</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Gorard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, S &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Hordosy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, R (2013) “What is school segregation and why should we care? Patterns of between-school segregation in England” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Paper presented at BERA 39</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:5.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic"> Annual Conference</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Machin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, S &amp; S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">va, O (2013) ‘School Structure, School Autonomy and The Tail’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Centre for Economic Performance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Wrigley, T &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Kalambouka</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, A (2012) ‘Academies and Achievement: setting the record straight’ www.changingschools.org.uk</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Academies Commission (2013) ‘Unleashing greatness: Getting the best from an academised system’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">RSA/Pearson</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">National Audit Office (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Establishing Free Schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">London: The Stationary Office</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/oct/25/flagship-free-school-kings-science-academy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/dec/13/discovery-free-school-crawley-closed-ofsted</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><a href="http://www.atl.org.uk/Images/120604%20Middle%20tier%20discussion%20paper%20AW.pdf"><span style="color:#1a6d8f; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.atl.org.uk/Images/120604%20Middle%20tier%20discussion%20paper%20AW.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; fo